  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal anti-money laundering (AML) practices emerged in the 1920s during Prohibition in the United States\n- Organized crime groups needed methods to disguise illegally obtained cash\n\n2. Initial Formal Legislation:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States was the first comprehensive legal framework\n- Required financial institutions to report large currency transactions\n- Established reporting requirements to track potential criminal financial activities\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established by G7 countries\n- Created international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n- Developed global regulatory framework for financial transparency\n\n4. Major Expansion:\n- United States Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- Expanded legal mechanisms for prosecuting financial crimes\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Added counter-terrorism financial tracking provisions\n- Increased reporting and monitoring requirements\n\n6. Global Compliance:\n- Increasing international cooperation\n- Most developed countries now have comprehensive AML legal frameworks\n- Continuous evolution of regulatory approaches\n\nThe legal history reflects growing complexity in addressing financial criminal activities.",
